57
00:02:56.161 --> 00:03:07.211
Incoming livestream: Now, how do we do that? We build defenses at the execution layer, which sits outside of, but works hand-in-hand with the reasoning layer of these agentic systems.

58
00:03:08.171 --> 00:03:21.820
Incoming livestream: So that brings me to our third model, just really quickly, because I'm sure you guys have, like, seen some version of this. This is our lens of looking at this. So when we're dealing with autonomous agents in this multi-tenant SaaS environment.

59
00:03:21.821 --> 00:03:31.970
Incoming livestream: We look at our threat landscapes in two buckets, essentially. Bucket one, your platform target attacks. So this involves attackers finding cracks in your implementation of this

60
00:03:31.971 --> 00:03:51.720
Incoming livestream: platform. So maybe that's a misconfigured permission set, or a flaw in the custom APEX skills are exposed to the reasoning engine. And then we have bucket two, which we call abuse of a legitimate agency. So these are threat actors using the agent's legitimate built-in capabilities to perform actions that are valid.

61
00:03:51.721 --> 00:03:53.731
Incoming livestream: But malicious in context.

62
00:03:53.731 --> 00:04:04.361
Incoming livestream: The bottom line here is, we aren't just defending against bad words here, we're defending a massive multi-tenant execution engine, where your legitimate logic is constantly evolving.

63
00:04:04.871 --> 00:04:28.220
Incoming livestream: A little bit on agent force. We do have a set of guardrails, which we call the trust layer. Not going to go into details, but you've seen this across industry. Pretty common to have this content moderation layer that focuses on the reasoning layer, right? So that's your dialogue between the user and the LLM. Well, that is critical for filtering and screening for things like toxicity and prompt injection.

64
00:04:28.221 --> 00:04:31.671
Incoming livestream: The content moderation alone is not enough.

65
00:04:31.671 --> 00:04:33.480
Incoming livestream: For the following reasons.

66
00:04:33.551 --> 00:04:49.521
Incoming livestream: First, what we touched upon a little bit earlier, is reasoning versus execution. So while you do have the content moderation layer that polices the reasoning layer, which is your thought process, the… it cannot see the actual execution layer, right? So that's the actual system calls.

67
00:04:49.521 --> 00:04:57.341
Incoming livestream: You also need guardrails that police the specific actions and invocations triggered by the agent.

68
00:04:57.341 --> 00:05:10.471
Incoming livestream: And then we also have the blocking dilemma. Because your content moderation layer often captures malicious intent, but lacks the high-fidelity signal required to do things like automated inline blocking.

69
00:05:10.471 --> 00:05:20.200
Incoming livestream: and an enterprise context. So what we develop here, this detection model, provides the behavioral context necessary to move from

70
00:05:20.201 --> 00:05:33.571
Incoming livestream: just flagging to confident, automated response. And then lastly, we have what we call the post-generation blindness. So, even if, in a scenario where your prompt is deemed as safe.

71
00:05:33.571 --> 00:05:43.271
Incoming livestream: The resulting authentic plan might involve an authorized data access, or privilege isolation that traditional content filters just cannot observe, hence act on.

72
00:05:43.771 --> 00:05:59.960
Incoming livestream: So with that, we walk through the challenges. What do we do, and how do we deal with that? I'll hand it off to Matt, and he'll walk you through our solution for that. Yeah, so now that we have this Agentic ecosystem in place, building detections around it really comes down to.

73
00:06:00.121 --> 00:06:13.490
Incoming livestream: how do you go about detecting anomalies? And historically, I think detection engineers have looked to anomaly detection as a pretty big part of the toolkit, but typically at the user level or around specific tables or entities.

74
00:06:13.491 --> 00:06:20.171
Incoming livestream: One of the things that I really want to highlight is changing in the GenAI era here, is that

75
00:06:20.291 --> 00:06:35.581
Incoming livestream: We no longer have to just be constrained to the user level. You can actually also consider the context of the agent itself as a new access for anomaly detection. Especially when you do this in the context of the organization that's building and deploying those agents.

76
00:06:35.581 --> 00:06:47.460
Incoming livestream: You essentially end up with 3 levels of context that you could use for anomaly detection. If you have a data science background, this lends itself extremely well to something called an ensemble model.

77
00:06:47.461 --> 00:07:06.350
Incoming livestream: Where you can start to really pair these different levels of context together, to minimize noise. I think anyone that's done anomaly detection knows that it can be very noisy, especially if kind of deployed quickly. So, combining these three streams together, and then using them to kind of reduce noise across

78
00:07:06.631 --> 00:07:11.291
Incoming livestream: Sorry, across all three, really helps make this a meaningful and impactful model.

79
00:07:14.581 --> 00:07:29.130
Incoming livestream: Yeah, so, we started by trying to quantify intent, and we did that with a simple and well-scoped hypothesis, which was just that looking for agents accessing things that they normally don't would be a good way to find anomalies in the ecosystem.

80
00:07:30.631 --> 00:07:37.110
Incoming livestream: When we had that hypothesis in place, we then started to look at what features could we actually put in place to measure

81
00:07:37.131 --> 00:07:54.590
Incoming livestream: those kinds of anomalies. So, we started looking at how frequently were Agentic sessions accessing data? What types of access were they doing? Are… are the agents just selecting data? Are they updating it? Are they deleting it? Can we build filters or features around that?

82
00:07:54.721 --> 00:08:04.690
Incoming livestream: And so by keeping those feature sets simple, and the hypothesis simple, we started being able to investigate where does our coverage work versus where does it not work.

83
00:08:04.801 --> 00:08:12.221
Incoming livestream: We started to find out, what are the legitimate edge cases, what are the issues with what we're measuring, is it effective or is it not?

84
00:08:14.391 --> 00:08:26.691
Incoming livestream: I want to talk through some of the features that we did look at that were pretty essential to how the model operated. So we really tried to consider data access from both kind of a depth standpoint and a breadth standpoint.

85
00:08:26.711 --> 00:08:39.331
Incoming livestream: We were looking at things like the frequency of calls to our databases, what proportion of data was actually being accessed by these agents, which gives you a good standpoint of depth, especially if you…

86
00:08:39.331 --> 00:08:50.530
Incoming livestream: are looking for data exfiltration. Is somebody pulling the entire database? Are they just accessing one customer's records? Really trying to understand, kind of, those ratios was pretty key for us.

87
00:08:52.271 --> 00:09:00.380
Incoming livestream: Another good thing that we looked at was we started to quantify the sensitivity or the rarity of the data being accessed, so…

88
00:09:00.521 --> 00:09:04.851
Incoming livestream: in the Salesforce database as you are kind of building these out.

89
00:09:04.881 --> 00:09:24.591
Incoming livestream: We have, feature flags for things like fields that might contain PII or sensitive data. We also try and do profiling to understand how frequently are agents touching certain columns or fields, and really understand what data is being accessed, how frequently, those kind of help to build out the features.

90
00:09:29.711 --> 00:09:40.671
Incoming livestream: So, as you kind of combine these things, we really looked to incremental historical profiling. So, every day, we would actually build a profile of all of the sessions that had occurred in a given day.

91
00:09:40.861 --> 00:09:53.581
Incoming livestream: This let us quickly assemble a historical context and a baseline, and then we were able to quickly identify anything that was actually out of character based on the historical baseline, so…

92
00:09:53.681 --> 00:10:03.331
Incoming livestream: As we continued to aggregate kind of a rolling history, it was really easy to look at standard deviations or anomalies kind of from that historical baseline.

93
00:10:04.331 --> 00:10:23.860
Incoming livestream: One of the benefits of this is that as new sessions occurred, we could really score them quickly after the session occurred, or even as it was ongoing, to identify our outliers and proactively respond. This kind of deviation-based or standard deviation-based scoring also helps kind of build alert prioritization into the system as well.

94
00:10:26.821 --> 00:10:44.681
Incoming livestream: I want to also cover some of the things that didn't work for us, and again, this is one of the major downsides to consider when building these ensemble models, is if you start to consider features across these multiple layers of identity, the number of features that you're going to be building into your models will explode very quickly, so…

95
00:10:45.351 --> 00:11:00.131
Incoming livestream: Every new data rarity or data frequency feature that you add, if you were looking at it in the context of the user, the agent, the org, you're building out multiple layers of these features, and it can create noise and complexity very quickly.

96
00:11:02.711 --> 00:11:14.620
Incoming livestream: I do also want to call out one of the things we built that didn't work, which was… we built a pretty large, query complexity calculator early on. It was custom-built, it took a lot of code. One of the…

97
00:11:14.761 --> 00:11:20.400
Incoming livestream: reasons that it didn't work for us, was just that it kind of confused layers of identity, so…

98
00:11:20.421 --> 00:11:39.991
Incoming livestream: We thought that malicious actors would essentially be looking to run these complicated queries, or that it would be a good way to identify anomalous queries. What we were finding was that the agents themselves were constructing the queries, so, just make sure that your features are measuring what you think they are measuring. It's a good way to find the edge cases that are important here.

99
00:11:41.121 --> 00:11:44.020
Incoming livestream: We also found a pain point in…

100
00:11:44.781 --> 00:11:59.111
Incoming livestream: joining data in from multiple tables, so we had to reach out to get, contextual information from metadata tables around the queries being executed. This built in a number of really expensive computational joins for us, so…

101
00:11:59.221 --> 00:12:03.201
Incoming livestream: Later on, we were able to actually refactor the model to

102
00:12:03.341 --> 00:12:09.660
Incoming livestream: Essentially operate on just one table, remove the expensive joins, and have the bottle train in a third of the time.

103
00:12:11.871 --> 00:12:18.120
Incoming livestream: At the end of the day, the results, speak for themselves. We had nearly 2 million daily prompts.

104
00:12:18.231 --> 00:12:29.301
Incoming livestream: Which we were able to filter down slightly through the trust layer, but through the behavioral anomaly detection model, at the end of the day, we had fewer than 30 active alerts that needed investigation.

105
00:12:32.261 --> 00:12:43.471
Incoming livestream: One of the things that we also did is we tried to lean into an agentic paradigm, where we now expect that agents are also going to be involved in the investigation and triage of the alerts.

106
00:12:43.751 --> 00:12:48.611
Incoming livestream: So, what you see on screen here is an actual example of an alert, but…

107
00:12:48.761 --> 00:12:56.650
Incoming livestream: What we're doing is creating a structured JSON payload that is then ingested by an additional agent that helps make sense of that payload.

108
00:12:57.371 --> 00:13:17.050
Incoming livestream: And so, the agent is able to very quickly take the features that we provided and synthesize a summary of why the alert is anomalous. Typically in plain English, and one of the advantages of that is it's very customer-facing, very friendly. We don't necessarily have to assume that the investigator has a security background.

109
00:13:19.231 --> 00:13:29.220
Incoming livestream: Thank you, Matt. So, we talked about, the state of the world that we've built this, tool into. Let's talk a little bit about the road ahead.

110
00:13:29.271 --> 00:13:38.760
Incoming livestream: So the ultimate goal for really any security practitioner is moving from knowing what happened yesterday to stopping what is happening now.

111
00:13:38.811 --> 00:13:50.690
Incoming livestream: So in our current pilot, version of this model, we accept a 12 to 24 hour detection latency, as both the training and inference pieces are running in batch jobs.

112
00:13:50.691 --> 00:14:04.121
Incoming livestream: However, our architecture is built for the hot path, so by taking the behavioral baseline we learned during our daily batch processing, and eventually pushing them to a high-speed cache, we could eventually perform the inference piece in flight.

113
00:14:04.131 --> 00:14:14.600
Incoming livestream: So if a session hits our critical threshold, meaning it's essentially statistically impossible for this to be normal behavior, we don't wait for SOC analysts to triage the alert.

114
00:14:14.601 --> 00:14:32.010
Incoming livestream: or, notify the customer hours, or sometimes days later, we move to auto-containment. We can kill the session, revoke the token, or trigger a bot-level lockdown immediately. This is how we'll eventually close the loop at the execution layer of an agentic system.

115
00:14:32.921 --> 00:14:57.801
Incoming livestream: Let's talk about some of the lessons we learned along the way. First one, our major hurdle was the observability gap. So in the beginning, we had these engineering logs that told us what happened, but the security telemetry didn't really tell us who or which agent was responsible for what in a way that supported what we wanted to do, which was high-fidelity detection. So your mission here really is what we call identity multitasking.

116
00:14:58.101 --> 00:15:18.010
Incoming livestream: You have to partner with your engineering and product teams early on to ensure that your authentic logs aren't just debug strings, they need to be structured events that link the invoking user ID to the agent ID. Because without this context, you're blind to the, abuse of a legitimate agency case, where

117
00:15:18.171 --> 00:15:23.961
Incoming livestream: You just cannot distinguish between what a power user is and what a compromised agent might look like.

118
00:15:24.271 --> 00:15:34.600
Incoming livestream: Secondly, don't wait for a known attack to build your defense. So, in the environment we operate in, where there's 12,000 plus unique daily active agents.

119
00:15:34.621 --> 00:15:51.320
Incoming livestream: A signature-based approach is essentially just a black box failure. You need to start profiling what normal looks like today, especially for, as a rarity, features like those that Matt has just walked you through. So then you have the statistical mean

120
00:15:51.321 --> 00:15:55.681
Incoming livestream: Ready when the deviation does occur, and then you can act on it immediately.

121
00:15:56.331 --> 00:16:04.631
Incoming livestream: Lesson number 3. Practitioners, ourselves included, often fall into the trap of building the perfect feature.

122
00:16:04.631 --> 00:16:23.280
Incoming livestream: We spent a significant amount of time and resources on this so-called parser and query complexity model that ultimately just introduced too much complexity and latency for what we eventually wanted to do, which is near time or real-time action. We found that simple telemetry, like

123
00:16:23.281 --> 00:16:31.340
Incoming livestream: invocation count or sensitive asset frequency, produced way higher fidelity signals without having to blow up our SLAs.

124
00:16:32.171 --> 00:16:47.061
Incoming livestream: And finally, remember that your funnel is only as good as your baseline. Do expect noise for the first 14 days of a new agent's life. Build that warm-up period into your SOX playbook so you don't burn out your analysts on day one.

125
00:16:47.381 --> 00:16:54.120
Incoming livestream: And with that, it's a wrap. We will open up to questions. Thank you so much for being here.

